Y1  - 2010/02/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2009.00577.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 213
EP  - 236
VL  - 51
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2009.00577.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In this article, policies are negotiated in a committee by playing a dynamic voting game with an endogenous default (or status quo) policy. I show that joining a committee by maintaining a strong agenda setting power is a way for a decision maker to commit to a policy that in absence of committees is not time consistent. The disciplinary role of the endogenous status quo and the heterogeneity of preferences within the committee are two crucial ingredients to obtain this result. As a motivating example, this article focuses on the time consistency of monetary policy.
ER  - 

